anadian and British forces. How did soldiers relate to suffering comrades? Did large numbers of shell shock cases affect the outcome of important battles? Was frontline psychiatric treatment as effective as many experts claimed after the war? Were Canadians treated any differently than other Commonwealth soldiers? A Weary Road is the first comprehensive study to address these important questions. Author Mark Osborne Humphries uses research from Canadian, British, and Australian archives, including hundreds of newly available hospital records and patient medical files, to provide a history of war trauma as it was experienced, treated, and managed by ordinary soldiers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aWar neurosesxDiagnosiszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar neurosesxTreatmentzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xMedical carezCanada. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh  aCanadian army.  aCanadian military history.  aGreat War.  aPTSD.  aWWI.  aWorld War I.  aWorld War One.  acombat stress.  amedical history.  amilitia.  ashell shock.  asoldiers.  atrauma.  atrench warfare.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266140040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442661400423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442661400.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles